DOCUMENT();       

loadMacros("PG.pl",
           "PGbasicmacros.pl",
#           "PGchoicemacros.pl",
           "PGanswermacros.pl",
#           "PGgraphmacros.pl",
#           "extraAnswerEvaluators.pl",
           "PGauxiliaryFunctions.pl",
"MathObjects.pl",
"AnswerFormatHelp.pl",
"PGcourse.pl",
           );
       
TEXT(beginproblem()); # standard preamble to each problem.

Context("Numeric")->variables->are(t=>"Real");

$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

$r = random(7.9,5.1,0.2);
$k = $r/100;
$p = random(15,32,1);
$a = $p*1000;

$ans_b = round( (1 - exp(-$k)) *100000)/1000;
$ans = "$a e^(-$k t)";

BEGIN_TEXT
A a population shrinks from its initial level of $p,000 at a continuous decay rate of $r$PERCENT per year.
$BR
$BR
(a) Find a formula for $BITALIC P(t)${EITALIC}, the population in $BITALIC t $EITALIC years.  
$BR
\( P(t) = \) \{ ans_rule(20) \}
\{ AnswerFormatHelp("formulas") \}
$BR
$BR
(b) By what percent does the population shrink each year? 
$BR
\{ ans_rule(10) \} $PERCENT 
${BITALIC}(Round to the nearest 0.001${PERCENT})${EITALIC}
\{ AnswerFormatHelp("numbers") \}
END_TEXT

ANS( Compute("$ans")->cmp() );
ANS( Compute("$ans_b")->cmp() );

#ANS( fun_cmp( $ans,vars=>'t' ) );
#ANS( num_cmp( $ans_b,tol=>0.0005 ) );

$dec = -$r/100;
$b = round(exp($dec)*100000)/100000;
$left = $b*100;

SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));
$BR $SPACE $BR 
$BBOLD  SOLUTION $EBOLD
$BR 

a) Since $BITALIC P(t) $EITALIC has continuous decay, its formula will be \( P(t)=P_0e^{kt} \).  Since \( P_0 \) is the initial population, which is $p,000, and \( k \) represents the continuous growth rate of -$r${PERCENT}, our formula is $BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE 
\( P(t)= $a e^{$dec t} \).
$BR $SPACE $BR
b) Rewriting \( P(t)=$a e^{$dec t} \) in the form \( P=$a b^t \) will help us accomplish this.  Thus, $BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE 
\( P(t) = $a (e^{$dec})^t \approx $a ($b)^t \). $BR
After each year, about $left${PERCENT} of the population remains,
so the population decreases by approximately $ans_b${PERCENT} per year.
$BR
END_SOLUTION
      

